The paper deals with combinatorial properties of words and their factorizations, which are typical topics in the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also discusses the use of Lyndon words and inverse Lyndon words in string comparison, which falls under the sub-category of cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory). Additionally, the paper involves the study of borders of words, which is a topic in the sub-category of cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The paper also uses some information theory concepts, such as mutual information, which is related to the sub-category of cs.IT (Information Theory). Finally, the paper presents some new results and properties, which could be of interest to researchers in the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning).
